observations.recommendation:
Recommendation
We recommended the following:
The Office of the Municipal Accountant, Office of the GSO and the Inventory Committee to immediately convene and conduct full reconciliation on the accounting records with results of the actual physical count based on the RPCPPE;
The Office of the Municipal Accountant to submit to the Office of the Auditor a reconciled Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELC) on all PPE accounts after the results of the reconciliation;
The Office of the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the balances of the PPE accounts presented in the financial statements are correct, reliable, verifiable and reconciled with its balances per schedules and the RPCPPE prepared by the Inventory Committee;
The Office of the Municipal Accountant and the Office of the GSO to strictly follow the procedures for the disposition of non-existing/missing PPEs provided in Items 7 and 8 of COA Circular No. 2020-006; and
The Office of the Municipal Mayor to strictly monitor the full implementation of the one-time cleansing of PPE.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following:
The GSO to replace PARs and PCs with ICS and SPCs for all PPEs reclassified as semi-expendable properties under its custody;
The GSO to prepare and submit RegSPI in identifying all semi-expendable properties existing in the books and already issued to the end-users;
The Office of the Municipal Accountant to draw adjusting entries for dropping from the books the cost and accumulated depreciation of those PPEs already issued but identified as semi-expendable properties and provide necessary disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements relative to the change of accounting policy and the accounts affected;
The Office of the Municipal Accountant to maintain SPLCs for semi-expendable properties; and,
The Office of the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to observe the guidelines relative to the semi-expendable properties in the abovementioned Circulars.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following to Management:
Maintain the practice of sending demand letters to employees with outstanding CAs requiring them to settle unliquidated CAs and do the same on a regular basis;
For CAs for Confidential Funds which were already liquidated, make the necessary follow-up to COA-ICFAU duly supported with a copy of the transmittal letters for the issuance of the Credit Notice;
For CAs for Confidential Funds which have not yet been liquidated, require the preparation of the appropriate liquidation documents by the SDOs concerned and submit to the COA-ICFAU at the earliest possible time;
For unliquidated CAs of personnel who are still in active service and after receiving the demand letters, still failed to settle their obligation nor made an appropriate justification, immediately withhold their salaries or any amount due them until balances have been fully settled;
Initiate action to recover unsettled CAs of personnel who were already separated from service upon failure by the latter to respond to demand letters;
Revisit the aging schedules of CAs and make the appropriate corrections to reflect the correct age of each CAs and personnel status and henceforth for the Municipal Accountant to make a thorough review of the Financial Statements prior to its issuance; and,
Require the Accountant to monitor outstanding CAs of every official and employee and report the status of their liquidations to the Local Chief Executive (LCE) on a regular basis for appropriate action by the latter.

Recommendation:
We recommended to Management the following:
Submit written justification for the inclusion of the project Completion of Proposed Legislative Building under the 20 per cent DF;
The Municipal Mayor, being the head of the Municipal Development Council (MDC), spearhead the appropriate planning of priority projects including the identification of specific target implementation dates of the projects;
The MDC ensure that the projects for inclusion in the 20 per cent DF are within the permissible boundaries of the development fund; and,
Conduct review and evaluation of PPAs and consider changes/realignments in the budget for projects which cannot be implemented or have residual balances during the year to other viable developmental projects, subject to the approval of the Sangguniang Bayan.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following to Management:
Submit an explanation why Management has not imposed liquidated damages against the contractor for the delay incurred in the completion of the infrastructure projects and for not strictly complying Annex E of the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184;
The Municipal Engineer re-evaluate the performance of the contractors for the above-mentioned projects for the possible imposition of liquidated damages, and submit to the audit team the computation of the same;
The Municipal Engineer ensure that all infrastructure projects are strictly monitored in accordance with plans and schedules of implementation so that available actions or remedies can be imposed against erring contractors; and,
The LCE require the project contractors to complete the construction of the above-mentioned projects and impose the appropriate liquidated damages and other sanctions provided in R.A. No. 9184 and its IRR.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following to Management:
Submit a written justification as to the recurring practice of not adhering to the procedures of competitive bidding or negotiated procurement in hiring consultants;
Furnish COA with copies of the basic documents required in COA Circular Nos. 2009-01 and 2012-01 in relation to the procurement of consulting services to show proof that management adhered strictly to the provisions under R.A. No. 9184 and its revised IRR in hiring consultants such as 	the following:
Approved Annual Procurement Plan;
BAC Resolution recommending the use of alternative mode if the same was the intention of management;
Copies of professional license and/or curriculum vitae of consultants,
Terms of reference;
Statement of scope of work expected output/deliverables and expected time frame, if not in the TOR;
Minimum requirements on the expertise of the consultants and the qualifications of individual personnel necessary for the undertaking, if not in the TOR; and
Other related documents;
Furnish COA with a Consultancy Progress Report duly prepared submitted by the consultant and approved by the end-user, indicating the actual number of output per checkpoint to validate its compliance to the required percentage output per checkpoint based on the contract	.

Recommendation (consolidated above):
Maximize the utilization of GAD Funds through employing effective and efficient measures in the implementation of GAD-related programs and projects through focusing on addressing the current gender issues and needs of its women constituents to attain the objectives in which funds were provided;
Reprogram those PPAs that are no longer responsive to the gender issues and needs of the women constituents in the community and implement it immediately; and
Strictly monitor the implementation of GAD projects and activities by conducting timely evaluation to ensure that these are implemented as planned to attain GAD’s goals and objectives.
Coordinate with the Management in the implementation of gender audit through sending them formal communication letters informing about the said activity, and the needs of the GFPS on its implementation;
Attend trainings and seminars about the conduct of gender audit through GMEF and GeRL Assessment Tool to equip them with adequate knowledge and skills in implementing the said program; and
Conduct gender audit on its agency through the use of GMEF and GeRL Assessment Tool.
LGU create and establish M&E Team in consonance with the provision of Section 5 of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 to evaluate the LGU GAD policies, programs and projects;
Attend trainings and seminars about the Gender M&E System to equip them with adequate knowledge and skills in implementing the said program; and
The Gender M&E Team to conduct evaluation on the LGU GAD policies, program and projects and submit a GAD Evaluation Report.

Recommendation
We recommended the following:
The Offices of the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer, respectively, to submit explanation to the audit team on the existence of unremitted contributions and/or loan amortizations of Philhealth, GSIS and Pag-IBIG due to the respective government corporations;
The Offices of the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer, respectively, to immediately conduct reconciliation on its existing records pertaining to membership contributions and/or loan payments to ensure exact and accurate amounts for withholding and remittance;
Immediately remit to the Philhealth, the GSIS, and the HDMF/Pag-IBIG the prior periods’ unremitted contributions of the LGU employees; and
Ensure full and timely withholding and remittance of monthly contributions in accordance with the schedule of payments prescribed by the said government corporations to avoid penalties.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following to management:
Maintain the practice of sending demand letters to employees with outstanding cash advances requiring them to settle unliquidated CAs and do the same on a regular basis;
For unliquidated cash advances of personnel who are still in active service and after receiving the demand letters, still failed to settle their obligation nor made an appropriate justification, immediately withhold their salaries or any amount due them until balances have been fully settled;
Make appropriate disclosures in the Notes to FS on the actual status of unliquidated cash advances for confidential fund, particularly those granted prior to the effectivity of COA-DBM JC 2015-01;
Furnish the Audit Team copies of transmittal letters on the liquidation documents for confidential funds submitted to COA-ICFAU, if any;
Prepare adjusting entry to record the cash advances totaling ₱74,750.00 to its appropriate account Advances to SDO from the Advances for Payroll account and furnish the Audit Team a copy of the Journal Entry Voucher;
Initiate action to recover unsettled CAs of personnel who were already separated from service upon failure by the latter to respond to demand letters;
Revisit the aging schedules of cash advances and make the appropriate corrections to reflect the correct age of each cash advances and personnel status;
Require the Accountant to monitor outstanding cash advances of every official & employee and report the status of their liquidations to the Local Chief Executive on a regular basis for appropriate action by the latter; and
The Municipal Accountant to make a thorough review of the Financial Statement prior to its issuance.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following to management:
The Inventory Committee review all individual RPCPPEs submitted by each team and submit a consolidated report for the same;
The GSO and Accounting Units undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and ensure that both records are regularly reconciled;
The GSO, Accounting Unit and the Inventory Committee fast track the implementation of their respective task to determine the correct balance of the PPE accounts;
Considering the period that lapsed from the last physical inventory count, the data of which do not include items procured thereafter, it is highly recommended that the Inventory Committee conduct another count to update the Physical Inventory Report; and
Succeeding procedures after the conduct of the Physical Inventory Count be immediately implemented in order to have an updated property records both at the GSO and Accounting Office, and to avoid wastage of time and effort by failing to utilize any available information as a result of the very tedious physical inventory count.

Recommendation:
We recommended to management the following:
Submit written justification or any equivalent document citing therein the reasons for inclusion of purchase of a utility van for Sangguniang Bayan under the 20% EDF;
Refrain from providing generic/lump sum appropriations in the Annual Budget and AIP, instead, identify and indicate specific PPAs;
Ensure that PPAs to be funded out of the 20% DF are well-planned and procurement-and -implementation-ready; and
Conduct review and evaluation of PPAs and consider changes/realignments in the budget for projects which cannot be implemented or have residual balances during the year to other viable developmental projects, subject to the approval of the Sangguniang Bayan.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following to the management:
Review the existing LGU personnel allocation and distribution to present the actual need of each department, division or office;
As far as practicable, LGU personnel to report to their original Department/Division where their salaries and wages are allocated and charged;
Stop the practice of charging Casual Plantilla employees assigned at different offices to the MPEE to avoid overstatement of the latter’s operational cost; and
Provide appropriate budget for salaries and wages at different Department/Division where the Casual Plantilla employees are reporting for appropriate charging.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following to management:
Submit a written explanation or justification on the construction of the two-storey operation center building even prior to the start of the procurement process;
The BAC submit result of any validation or confirmation that the contractor did not make any misrepresentation of its submitted Statement of All On-going Projects;
Submit the CY 2022 Audited FS or any equivalent document to support the computation of the contractor’s NFCC;
Submit a copy of a duly-received Letter of Invitation to two other observers to attend the post-qualification activity, if any, and ensure that all observers as required under RA No. 9184 and its Revised IRR are invited to attend, witness or observe during the eligibility checking, shortlisting, pre-bid conference, preliminary examination of bids, bid evaluation, and post-qualification;
Avoid giving preference to any project contractor to uphold the governing principle of competitiveness of government procurement; and
The LGU strengthen their procurement proceeding to ensure efficient and effective delivery of all procurement activities in accordance with RA No. 9184 and its Revised IRR.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following to management:
The LCE to submit a consolidated written explanation and/or comment on the above-noted deficiencies in the implementation of the subject infrastructure projects particularly on the following:
Failure to act on the projects’ status of implementation despite having a percentage of completion falling behind what is expected, hence the possibility of a negative slippage;
Approval of the request for suspension notwithstanding the absence of supporting documents and despite receipt of said request after the expiration of the contract duration;
Basis in the grant of approval on the request for suspension of work;
Continuation of work by the contractor despite having an approved request for suspension;
Certifying the Tennis Court Project as 100% completed, contrary to the result of the Auditor’s Inspection together with the Municipal Engineering personnel that the pavement is short by 382.17 square meters; and
Certifying the Tambunan Project as 100% completed, contrary to the result of the Auditor’s Inspection that the same were not compacted and leveled thoroughly as there are still protruding boulders and piles of stone and soil;
The LCE and/or the Municipal Engineer to submit appropriate and relevant documents to support the approval of the request for suspension, if any, such as certification or report from PAG-ASA on the unfavorable weather condition and certification or any equivalent document on the closure of quarry site and that no other sources or alternative supplier are available from appropriate government entity;
The LCE to require all contractors requesting suspension of work or time extension to attached appropriate documents to support the cause or reason for the said request and conduct validation and confirmation to check the truthfulness of the same prior to approval;
The Municipal Engineer to inform all contractors that any request for suspension of work or extension of time be submitted prior to the expiration of contract duration and that all request must be attached with appropriate supporting documents;
The Municipal Engineer re-evaluate the performance of the contractors for the above-mentioned projects for the possible imposition of liquidated damages, and submit to audit team the computation for the same;
The Municipal Engineer to ensure that all infrastructure projects are strictly monitored in accordance with plans and schedules of implementation so that available actions or remedies can be imposed against erring contractors;
Project Inspectorate Team to inspect and verify thoroughly the accomplishment claimed by the contractor and not to affix their signature if upon inspection and verification of accomplishment, the same is not in accordance with specifications provided for in the contract;
The LCE require the project contractor of the Tennis Court to complete the construction of the pavement found to be short by approximately 382.17 square meters and impose the appropriate liquidated damages; and
Management to implement and impose appropriate actions and remedies pursuant to the relevant provision of Republic Act (RA) 9184 and its Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR), such as the possible imposition of the penalty of suspension from participating in the public bidding process and issuance of blacklisting order, if warranted.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following to management:
The Municipal Accountant, Budget Officer and the LDRRMO discussed among themselves the noted deficiencies above and provide the Audit Team an explanation presented per item to clarify confusions and to correct any mistakes in order to present a reliable data and/or information needed by the users of information;
The Municipal Accountant review the amounts reflected on the Disclosures of LDRRM Fund in the Notes to Financial Statements to avoid computational error;
The Municipal Accountant refer to the previous years Disclosures of LDRRM Fund to avoid erroneous carry – over of ending balances to the succeeding year disclosure;
The Municipal Accountant properly disclose the amount and details of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF in the Notes to Financial Statements; and
The Municipal Accountant coordinate with the LDRRMO and the Budget Office in the preparation of the LDRRMF reports to avoid inconsistent information.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following to management:
The Municipal Accountant and the LDRRMO determine the correct amount of the LDRRMF-CO that remained unexpended as of December 31, 2023 based on available records and reconcile the same to the list of prior years’ LDRRM PPAs funded out of the LDRRMF-CO that remains unimplemented as of year-end;
The Municipal Accountant make the necessary adjusting entries to return any remaining balance of the unexpended LDRRMF-CO to the general fund;
The Municipal Accountant transfer only the unexpended/unobligated LDRRMF QRF/MOOE to the Special Trust Fund under Trust Liability-DRRM account excluding the unexpended LDRRMF-CO; and
The Municipal Accountant and LDRRM Officer to facilitate the immediate transfer of the LDRRMF-CO back to the general fund books and general fund bank account.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following to management:
The Municipal Accountant and LDRRMO, in coordination with the budget office, validate the balances presented in CY 2023 Notes to FS and other reports on LDRRM and determine its budget composition to check whether the same still include LDRRM Funding for capital outlay;
The Municipal Accountant and LDRRMO facilitate the transfer of the unexpended LDRRMF QRF/MOOE that had already lapsed to the general fund;
The Local Sanggunian enact a local ordinance appropriating unexpended LDRRMF that is reverted to the general fund only for other social services as required under Section 21 of Republic Act No. 10121 and Section 5.1.13 of COA Circular No. 2012-002, if any; and
The Municipal Accountant and LDRRMO, closely monitor the utilization of LDRRMF, particularly those which are unexpended in a current year, to ensure optimum utilization in compliance with applicable laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended that:

a)	The Municipal Accountant prepare and submit to COA Office the monthly BRS within the reglementary period as required under COA Circular No. 96-011 and record the adjustments for any reconciling item;

b)	The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer reconcile regularly their respective cash records together with the records of the depository banks pertaining to the cash accounts of the agency to detect instantly errors either by the bank, Accounting unit or Cash unit; 

c)	The Municipal Accountant verify the cause of the “DA BUB 2016 - 4 units” fund having a negative book balance of P68,387.92 and prepare the appropriate adjustment to correct the error; and

d)	Make the necessary adjustment for the P 0.01 noted deficiency and other reconciling items and provide a written explanation for funds with negative balances.

We recommended the following:

a)	The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant implement the procedures as provided under Section 59 of COA Circular No. 2002-003 dated June 20, 2002 on Spoiled and Stale Checks;

b)	Identify other stale checks through the preparation of BRS for other bank accounts;

c)	The Municipal Accountant inform the Municipal Treasurer in writing about the stale checks noted in the BRS;

d)	The Municipal Treasurer determine the status of the Stale Checks and prepare a report of stale checks which were already claimed by the payees and stale checks which were unreleased to payees and still on hand;

e)	The Municipal Treasurer send communications to the concerned payees or creditors informing them on the status of the checks. If the concerned payees or creditors appeared to claim the checks or requested for a re-issuance of the stale checks, the Municipal Treasurer issue a new check to the claimant in accordance with the procedures provided under Section 59 of COA Circular No. 2002-003 on Spoiled and Stale Checks; and

f)	After exhaustion of the communication phase and there are still unclaimed checks in the possession of the Municipal Treasurer, the latter submit the necessary documents to the Municipal Accountant for the recording of the Accounts Payable.

We reiterated our recommendations for management to:

a)	Send demand letters immediately to employees with outstanding cash advances and require   them to settle unliquidated CAs. If liquidation is still not achieved, consider withholding their salaries or any amount due them until balances have been fully settled;

b)	Cease from granting additional CAs to officers/employees with unsettled CAs;

c)	Record the liquidation of CAs for confidential funds granted after the effectivity of COA-DBM Joint Circular 2015-01 duly supported with copy of transmittal letter duly received by COA-ICFAU; and 

d)	Require the Accountant to monitor outstanding cash advances of every official & employee and report the status of their liquidations to management.

We recommended the following to management:

a)	Make confirmations of all recorded payables to check whether said claims actually exist or not especially those long outstanding payables and consider the reversion of those payables with no actual claimant after exhausting all necessary remedy to validate the existence of such obligations;

b)	The accounting office monitor the status of all disbursement vouchers released by them after checking the completeness of its supporting documents to check whether payment has already been made or not;

c)	The accounting office ensure that all payables recorded in the books of the LGU are adequately supported with necessary documents; and

d)	Payments of all payables with valid claimants and complete supporting documents be immediately made in accordance with the applicable rules and regulations and upon the presumption that budgets for these obligations were already earmarked through the Obligation Request duly signed by the budget officer to avoid accumulation of unpaid obligations.

We recommended the following to management:

a)	Concerned office having custody of the transaction documents with valid obligation and with DV signed by the Municipal Accountant immediately processed the same for approval and for subsequent payment thereof;

b)	Concerned office having custody of the transaction documents with valid obligation transmit the same to the accounting office for purposes of pre-audit and checking as to completeness of supporting documents;

c)	If found to have complete supporting documents, the Municipal Accountant sign the Disbursement Voucher and submit the same for approval and for subsequent payment thereof. For DVs with incomplete supporting documents, return the same to the concerned office and inform the latter in writing of the lacking documents which needs to be complied. The accounting office may consider having a template or official form to be used in cases where transmitted transaction documents are found to have incomplete supporting documents or deficiencies;

d)	Concerned office immediately comply the lacking documents and correct any deficiencies noted and officially transmit the transaction documents after compliance therewith;

e)	The Budget Officer ensure that Obligation Request is duly signed by the requesting office before signing the same; 

f)	The Budget Officer re-evaluate the Obligation Requests which were found to have alterations. Concerned officials and employees to avoid making alterations in the Obligation Request and in any transaction documents. In cases where alterations could never be avoided, ensure that any alteration is countersigned by all signatories; and

g)	Submit justification for the deficiencies noted particularly the alterations made on the ObR, and the non-submission of the DVs and supporting documents within a reasonable time despite its having been obligated already for a long time.

We recommended the following to management:

a)	Ensure compliance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 in the conduct of the physical inventory count and other related activity;

b)	Create an Inventory Committee with adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory in three months or less;

c)	Designate members of the Inventory Committee who may be able to devote their full time in the conduct of the physical inventory taking until the same is completed; and

d)	The inventory committee conduct the physical inventory count in accordance with an approved Physical Inventory Plan.

We recommended the following to management:

a)	All concerned personnel ensure that necessary documents under their responsibility are properly and completely filled-up;

b)	The Municipal Accountant ensure that supporting documents attached to the DV are valid and are properly and completely filled-up;

c)	Payments for items procured be made only after the same is completely delivered by the supplier in accordance with the contract;

d)	Correct all the deficiencies noted and submit the lacking documents;

e)	Delivered items should be inspected by the inspectorate team created by the municipality and accepted by the GSO;

f)	Recipients of items requested sign and acknowledge only an ICS, for semi-expendable items, and PAR for capitalizable assets or PPE, if the same were actually received by them;

g)	The Chairman of the Local School Board submit a written explanation why he signed the PAR for all 10 units of laptop when he only received one, and why he signed the PAR for the 29 units of ink jet printer when the same were not yet issued to him; and

h)	The Municipal Accountant submit a written justification for certifying the DV as to propriety despite insufficiency and incompleteness of supporting documents.

We recommended the following to management:

a)	Furnish COA with copies of the basic documents required in relation to the procurement of consulting services to show proof that management adhere strictly to the provisions provided under RA No. 9184 and its revised IRR in hiring consultants such as the following:

Approved Annual Procurement Plan;

BAC resolution recommending the use of alternative mode if the same was the intention of management;

Copies of professional license and/or curriculum vitae of consultants,

Terms of reference;

Technical and financial proposals;

Statement of scope of work expected outputs/deliverables and expected time frame, if not in the TOR;

Minimum requirements on the expertise of the consultants and the qualifications of individual personnel necessary for the undertaking, if not in the TOR; and 

Other related documents

b)	Furnish COA with copies of Consultancy Service Contracts that clearly defined the contract period, scopes of work, expected outputs/deliverables, terms of reference and time frames for purposes of evaluation with the actual accomplishment. Also include a report on the LGU situation during the time of hiring the consultants with specific details which gave rise to the necessity of hiring consultants; and

c)	Require the submission of a Consultancy Progress Report from all hired consultant to check whether the purpose for hiring consultants were actually achieved, and submit the same to COA.

We recommended the following to management:

a)	Explain in writing the reasons for directly hiring the IT experts instead of procuring the computer system in accordance with RA No. 9184 and its revised IRR, or through consulting services;

b)	Review the accomplishment reports of each IT experts and explain in writing the tasks which were found to be unaccomplished or incomplete but otherwise reported as 100% accomplished as checked, verified and approved by LGU officials and/or personnel;

c)	Submit any lacking documents as mentioned;

d)	Demand the IT Experts to finish the computerization program as per contract and scope of work; and

e)	File appropriate legal actions if the latter failed to comply the demand to perform his/her responsibilities as stipulated in the contract.

We recommended that management, on regular basis:

a)	Provide the Office of the Auditor at the beginning of the year with a list of all on-going government PPAs and those that are to be implemented during the year;

b)	Inform the Office of the Auditor within ten (10) days after the award of the infrastructure project or before the start of the program/activity that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted;

Recommendation:
We would like to reiterate our previous recommendations to management, as follows:
Send demand letters immediately to employees with outstanding cash advances and require   them to settle unliquidated CAs. If liquidation is still not achieved, consider withholding their salaries or any amount due them until balances have been fully settled;
Immediately furnished the audit team with the copies of the Demand Letter duly received by the concerned accountable officers;
Cease from granting additional CAs to officers/employees with unsettled CAs;
Record the liquidation of CAs for confidential funds granted after the effectivity of COA-DBM Joint Circular 2015-01 duly supported with copy of transmittal letter duly received by COA-ICFAU;
Initiate action to recover unsettled CAs of personnel who were already separated from service upon failure by the latter to respond to demand letters;
Stop the practice of transferring cash advances from one accountable officer to another who are not designated as disbursing officer and unbonded; and
Require the Accountant to monitor outstanding cash advances of every official & employee and report the status of their liquidations to management.
Management’s Comment:
Management has not yet submitted its written comment on this observation and recommendation. However, they commented during the exit conference that they will resolve all the issues raised and ensure that all concerned accountable personnel will be immediately informed of their obligations. As to the cash advances for confidential funds, the LCE commented that as far as he is concerned, all liquidation documents of his previous cash advances, except for the recent ones, were already submitted to COA-ICFAU. He will gather all the documents and submit the same to the Audit Team and to the Accounting Office for purpose of recording and record keeping.

Recommendation:
To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
to conduct risk assessment;
to identify critical processes and functions;
to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;
to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.
We also recommended that Management improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.
Management’s Comment:
Management has not yet submitted its written comment on this observation and recommendation. However, they responded during the exit conference that they find it hard to accomplish said requirement as this is new to them and they don’t have any document from which they can benchmark the formulation of their PSCP. They will do whatever they can and make coordination with other LGUs who also faces the same concern.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following to management:
Ensure compliance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 in the conduct of the physical inventory count and other related activity;
The Property and Accounting Unit complete the necessary preliminary activities and submit all documents to the Inventory Committee;
The Inventory Committee  finalize and submit the PIP and start the conduct of physical inventory and complete the same in three months or less;
Designate members of the Inventory Committee who may be able to devote their full time in the conduct of the physical inventory taking until the same is completed; and
The inventory committee conduct the physical inventory count in accordance with an approved Physical Inventory Plan.
Management’s Comment:
Management has not yet submitted its written comment on this observation and recommendation. However, they acknowledged the noted deficiency during the exit conference and responded that they will follow the auditor’s recommendation.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following to management:
Follow-up project implementation with the respective barangays and submit to the Audit Team a report and the reason for its non-completion or delayed/non- implementation;
Prepare a pro-forma MOA to be entered into by the authorized Municipal and Barangay Officials which clearly provides for the duties and responsibilities of the parties in the implementation of projects,  to include but not limited to (1) timeline of implementation; (2) manner of reporting and monitoring project implementation; (3) ownership upon project completion  and (4) recipient barangay’s obligation to account for the utilization of funds received and submission of liquidation report to the municipality;
Submit the lacking documents to the audit team;
Assign an LGU personnel to monitor the implementation of projects funded out of LGU funds and implemented by its component barangays; and
Require recipient barangays to submit liquidation report of the funds received from the LGU for the implementation of a specific project.
Management’s Comment:
Management has not yet submitted its written comment on this observation and recommendation. However, they acknowledged the noted deficiency during the exit conference and responded that they will follow the auditor’s recommendation.

We recommended the following to management:

a)	Create an Inventory Committee to conduct the required physical inventory count of all LGU properties including all local roads under the LGU’s jurisdiction;

b)	Create a sub-committee or group under the Municipal Inventory Committee that will primarily handle the inventory of local road network system;

c)	The Municipal Engineer, in coordination with the Inventory Committee, provide the local accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

d)	The GSO render the Report of Local Road Network at the end of the accounting period and maintain the following:
•	Local Road Inventory and Road Map
•	Complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components (Annex E of COA Circular No. 2015-008);

e)	The Municipal Accountant provide adjusting journal entries to recognize changes upon completion of the required inventory reports and reconciliation with the Registry of Public Infrastructure, and prepare and maintain the following:
•	Subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network
•	Lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component of road networks at the end of the year; and

f)	Depreciation be provided accordingly.

We recommended that management:

a)	Submit the job order contracts for purposes of evaluation with the submitted accomplishment reports;

b)	Furnished the audit team a copy of attendance logbooks or any form of documents that would indicate attendance of personnel on field work particularly those who are exempted from biometrics for validation purposes;

c)	Require the maintenance of attendance logbooks or any other means of recording attendance indicating respective names and signatures as well as the time of arrival to and departure from the office in support to manual DTR; and

d)	Instruct the HRMO to institute frequent monitoring to validate actual rendition of duties and responsibilities.

We reiterated our recommendations for management to:

a)	Send demand letters immediately to employees with outstanding cash advances and require   them to settle unliquidated CAs. If liquidation is still not achieved, consider withholding their salaries or any amount due them until balances have been fully settled;



b)	Cease from granting additional CAs to officers/employees with unsettled CAs;



